summary: EW Quotes and S8 Speculation
body:
EW Quotes and S8 Speculation

Sansa and Arya Stark

Sophie Turner: “Sansa this season is very much enjoying becoming a leader in her own right, and this year there are certain challenges by people who threaten that.”

  • House Stark already had its Winterfell plot last season where it seemed that it was Stark against Stark so it stands to reason the challenges are from outside the Stark circle this season.

Maisie Williams: “There’s this split with Arya between trying to be who she wants to be — getting back to back to that naiveté and innocence with her family — and her unfinished business.”

  • If Gendry is still going North with Jon, hopefully he’ll help Arya get some of that back.
  • What unfinished business? Probably her kill list, right?

Samwell Tary

John Bradley: “Sam is really feeling the responsibility of this information. But he knows Jon would rather hear this from Sam than anybody else.”

  • So Sam will most likely be there and be the one to tel Jon of his parentage.

Euron Greyjoy

Pilou Asbaek: “He wants to become the king of the Seven Kingdoms, yet he’s also blackmailing Cersei.”

  • What is he blackmailing her with? Blackmailing means there is something that he is in possession of (information? Weapons?) that could hurt Cersei. What could it be?
  • Does it have to do with her pregnancy?

The Hound

Rory McCann: “There will be a chance of squaring up to his brother and facing those demons.”

  • Unless the Mountain goes North, I’m assuming the Hound survives e3 and makes it to KL to confront his brother.

Bran Stark

Isaac Hempstead-Wright: “We see a slightly wiser Bran this year, who’s less like robot overload.”

  • THANK GOD BRAN WILL RECOVER SOME OF HIS PERSONALITY.

title: Jojen Reed in a nutshell
body:
Jojen: Bran, you must leave Winterfell and travel north of The Wall.

Bran: But I don’t want to leave Winterfell. I dreamt of being a knight.

Jojen: Well, I dreamt of going all this way–and then some–so I can be dinner for a guy who would rather eat my sister. Nut-up, Bran, them’s the breaks.

summary:
Last Hope: For Bran to meet and forgive Jaime 
Lannister. The final season has a lot of ground to cover, but if there 
isn't...
body:
Last Hope: For Bran to meet and forgive Jaime Lannister. The final season has a lot of ground to cover, but if there isn’t room spared for Bran meeting the man who crippled him, consider it a huge missed opportunity. For one thing, it’s a chance to humanize Bran again, after his recent turn toward detachment. What’s more, the series has already put the wheels in motion for Bran to give Jaime a fair chance. In season six, Bran briefly saw flashes of the Mad King Aerys on the night he tried to burn King’s Landing to the ground. If Bran has seen the Mad King’s final night, then he’s either seen or has access to the “tapes” of Jaime killing the man, becoming Kingslayer in the process. The fuller picture Jaime once tried to pitch to Brienne? Bran could see it for himself, and find it in him to absolve Jaime more fully. For the sake of a strong showing between Isaac Hempstead Wright and Nikolaj Coster-Waldau, here’s hoping some version of this scene comes to pass.

https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/game-thrones-final-season-bran-stark-predictions-1191103

Why should Bran forgive Jaime Lannister? Has Jaime done anything to deserve forgiveness? Has Jaime ever repented his trying to murder Bran to cover up his adultery? From season one to season 7, Jaime has continued to try to destroy the Starks. Hell, just two seasons back he threatened to trebuchet Bran’s cousin to get Riverrun for the Freys - the Stark’s bitter enemies who betrayed Robb and slaughtered him and many Northmen.

I can see Bran working with Jaime for the greater good and being united against a common threat. But forgiveness for crippling him? Just because Jaime killed the mad king to protect KL, Bran has to forgive him for trying to murder a 7 year old child?

I want to see Jaime show some actual remorse for all the bad shit he’s done over 7 seasons first. Before anyone forgives him. Till then I much prefer Cersei and her evilness compared to Jaime and his faux honor. At least Cersei is self-aware of what she is and what she’s done. Jaime is equally complicit and then pretends to be some noble do gooder.

Hell, just two seasons back he threatened to trebuchet Bran’s cousin to get Riverrun for the Freys - the Stark’s bitter enemies who betrayed Robb and slaughtered him and many Northmen.

I can see Bran working with Jaime for the greater good and being united against a common threat. But forgiveness for crippling him? Just because Jaime killed the mad king to protect KL, Bran has to forgive him for trying to murder a 7 year old child?

I want to see Jaime show some actual remorse for all the bad shit he’s done over 7 seasons first. Before anyone forgives him. Till then I much prefer Cersei and her evilness compared to Jaime and his faux honor. At least Cersei is self-aware of what she is and what she’s done. Jaime is equally complicit and then pretends to be some noble do gooder.
